content:
The special wrap-span">counsel does not appear to have provided a case for wrap-span">wrap-span">impeaching the president

“IT WAS a complete and total wrap-span">exoneration!” crowed Donald Trump on March 24th, shortly after his wrap-span">attorney-general released a four-page summary of Robert Mueller’s findings. “This was an illegal takedown that failed.” 

The president’s wrap-span">euphoria was wrap-span">understandable. After spending 22 months investigating the Russian campaign to rig the 2016 election in Mr Trump’s favour, the special wrap-span">counsel did not find that the president had a case to answer. Yet nor did he wrap-span">wrap-span">exonerate him on all counts. 

First the good news for Mr Trump. On the most serious area of wrongdoing Mr Mueller considered, according to wrap-span">Attorney-General William Barr’s summary, he “did not establish that members of the Trump Campaign wrap-span">conspired or wrap-span">coordinated with the Russian government in election wrap-span">interference activities.”

That does not mean Mr Trump’s campaign did not wrap-span">cooperate with the Russian effort. Over the course of Mr Mueller’s investigation several wrap-span">apparent instances of cooperation have come to light. Paul Manafort, the president’s former campaign chairman—who thanks to Mr Mueller is now serving a seven-and-a-half year prison sentence—shared campaign polling data with an wrap-span">alleged Russian agent, for example. And it is possible that Mr Mueller found more such instances. Yet he clearly found no “smoking-gun” evidence that the Trump team were witting wrap-span">participants in the Russian plot. Their dealings with Russians, according to the summary, did not amount to a “wrap-span">conspiracy” or an “agreement—wrap-span">tacit or express...on election wrap-span">interference”.

It will take a wrap-span">fuller wrap-span">disclosure of Mr Mueller’s findings, which Mr Barr has promised, to wrap-span">ascertain quite how reassuring this conclusion is. But it is nonetheless a big win for the president. Despite the nagging wrap-span">caveats—given his team’s many lies, wrap-span">evasions and wrap-span">demonstrable openness to receiving Russian help—it comes as close to corroborating the president’s “NO wrap-span">COLLUSION!!” wrap-span">assertion as he could possibly have hoped.

It will not wrap-span">deter House Democrats from continuing their ongoing wrap-span">Congressional wrap-span">probes into Mr Trump’s affairs and Russia. Nor should it. wrap-span">Congressional wrap-span">oversight is different from special wrap-span">counsel investigations. It aims to provide a public wrap-span">reckoning of behaviour wrap-span">antithetical to the public interest, even when that does not rise to the level of wrap-span">criminality, the yardstick Mr Mueller was wrap-span">mandated to consider. And there remain many wrap-span">unanswered questions about Mr Trump’s strange relationship with Russia (for example, why was it so keen to see him elected in the first place?) that it seems Mr Mueller either did not consider or has not resolved. 

Nonetheless, the special wrap-span">counsel appears to have wrap-span">allayed the biggest fear of all: that America’s sitting president was a wrap-span">traitorous wrap-span">accomplice to the Russia plot. Good as this is for Mr Trump, it is even better for America, and the Democrats’ wrap-span">oversight effort should be guided by it. If Mr Mueller did not find a smoking gun, they should not expect to.   

The other main part of Mr Mueller’s wrap-span">inquiry was a closer run thing. Mr Barr’s summary confirms that the special wrap-span">counsel looked into “a number of actions by the president” that might have wrap-span">constituted an illegal effort to wrap-span">wrap-span">obstruct investigations into the Russian plot. The main investigation, by the FBI, was handed over to Mr Mueller in part because of Mr Trump’s decision to wrap-span">sack the wrap-span">bureau’s then director, James Comey. That was one such action. The president’s wrap-span">subsequent effort to wrap-span">sack Mr Mueller, whose investigation he wrap-span">dubbed a “wrap-span">witch-hunt”, perhaps wrap-span">constituted another. 

Both steps looked bad for the president. Yet it was always wrap-span">moot whether they could be wrap-span">conclusively seen as wrap-span">wrap-span">obstruction, given that Mr Trump was wrap-span">empowered by his office to remove both men. Most legal experts think a president can be guilty of wrap-span">wrap-span">obstruction, even when exercising the wrap-span">legitimate powers of his office, if his wrap-span">motives are wrap-span">malign. And wrap-span">sacking Mr Comey in an effort to shut down the Russian investigation would certainly appear to fit that description.

Other experts—not wrap-span">insignificantly including Mr Barr—maintained that a president could not be guilty of wrap-span">wrap-span">obstruction when acting within his legal powers. In the end Mr Mueller, wrap-span">mindful of this wrap-span">thorny legal disagreement, decided not to try to settle it.

According to the wrap-span">attorney-general’s summary of his conclusions, he relayed his findings on Mr Trump’s wrap-span">dubious actions without concluding whether or not they wrap-span">constituted wrap-span">clinching evidence of wrap-span">wrap-span">obstruction. Instead Mr Mueller provided arguments on both sides of the question. According to Mr Barr, “the special wrap-span">counsel states that ‘while this report does not conclude that the president committed a crime, it does not wrap-span">wrap-span">exonerate him either.’”

The wrap-span">attorney-general—who last month returned to the wrap-span">helm of the Justice Department, having previously run it for George H. W. Bush—took it upon himself to settle the matter. He and his wrap-span">deputy, Rod Rosenstein, wrap-span">duly concluded that the evidence provided by Mr Mueller was not wrap-span">sufficient to “establish that the president committed an wrap-span">wrap-span">obstruction of justice offence.” Given Mr Barr’s wrap-span">afore-stated views, this was not terribly surprising. Though the wrap-span">attorney-general in fact offered a different argument in support of their finding. As Mr Mueller had not found the president to be engaged in a wrap-span">conspiracy with Russia, Mr Barr argued, it would be hard to establish that Mr Trump’s wrap-span">quasi-wrap-span">wrap-span">obstructive exercise of his powers was ill-intended.

That might sound like a wrap-span">stretch. The many dodgy ties between Mr Trump and Russia, and his and his wrap-span">associates’ record of lying about them, suggested he had highly wrap-span">questionable wrap-span">motives—short of a grand election-rigging wrap-span">conspiracy—to shut the Russia wrap-span">probe down. In any event, Mr Trump’s wrap-span">opponents will home in on the wrap-span">implication that Mr Mueller provided evidence of wrap-span">wrap-span">obstruction, which he felt unable to wrap-span">wrap-span">exonerate the president on, notwithstanding the legal arguments in favour of doing so. The Democrats will now fight to obtain the details of Mr Mueller’s reporting on this issue.

That battle will shortly take on a political life of its own. In his summary Mr Barr wrap-span">reiterated that, “wrap-span">mindful of the public interest in this matter”, he hoped to make as much of the special wrap-span">counsel’s report public as he could, “wrap-span">wrap-span">consistent with wrap-span">applicable law, regulations, and wrap-span">departmental policies.” Yet that could keep a lot of Mr Mueller’s report under wraps.

Mr Barr noted a wrap-span">provision against wrap-span">disclosure of information brought before a grand wrap-span">jury, which Mr Mueller made heavy use of. He also noted his need to protect material wrap-span">relevant to ongoing investigations, of which Mr Mueller has wrap-span">sparked several, wrap-span">notably including one by the US wrap-span">attorney’s office in the Southern District of New York that is looking into various aspects of Mr Trump’s affairs. Democrats who feel wrap-span">bruised by Mr Mueller’s failure to hang the president will console themselves by getting wrap-span">stuck into the new fight with Mr Barr over wrap-span">disclosure.

But they should not feel wrap-span">bruised. The notion that the special wrap-span">counsel was about to take down Mr Trump has long owed more to wrap-span">feverish wrap-span">Democratic wrap-span">imaginations than reality. The wrap-span">reams of evidence the special wrap-span">counsel has already made public, in hundreds of pages of court filings, did not point to a grand wrap-span">conspiracy between the Trump team and Russian agents. The wrap-span">wrap-span">obstruction case looked hard to prove.

If anything, the heavy burden of proof the special wrap-span">counsel was labouring under made his investigation look like a wrap-span">distraction from the more wrap-span">salient political questions surrounding Mr Trump’s dealings with Russia. For example: do American voters think it acceptable that their president continues to deny the existence of an attack on their democracy by a wrap-span">hostile power, which he has wrap-span">wrap-span">consistently lied about his links to, may owe his job to, and which he has done hardly anything to wrap-span">deter from continuing its wrap-span">assault?

Democrats might also feel Mr Mueller has done them a wrap-span">tactical favour. A more damning report on Mr Trump, including a clear wrap-span">allegation of wrap-span">criminality, would have made it hard for them to avoid wrap-span">wrap-span">impeaching him. Yet that course of action has always looked like a hiding to nothing. Protected by his party, Mr Trump almost certainly could not be removed by wrap-span">wrap-span">impeachment wrap-span">proceedings, and might well be strengthened by a failed effort. wrap-span">Democratic leaders know this perfectly well. Despite well-publicised calls for Mr Trump’s wrap-span">wrap-span">impeachment from a few wrap-span">hotheads, most Democrats in Congress are against it.

The best they could have hoped for from Mr Mueller was therefore a report that justified their continuing wrap-span">oversight operations against Mr Trump, without forcing them to wrap-span">wrap-span">impeach him. The special wrap-span">counsel appears to have delivered something close to that.

In a more wrap-span">abstract sense, indeed, his report appears almost as a wrap-span">rebuke to those who look to the law to solve political problems. Mr Mueller would not put it like this: the celebrated wrap-span">prosecutor is too wrap-span">fastidious and wrap-span">discreet. Yet his conclusions, in so far as Mr Barr has wrap-span">represented them wrap-span">accurately, appear to have added a few important wrap-span">embellishments to the Trump wrap-span">saga, and then kicked it back into the political wrap-span">realm where it belongs. Voters, not wrap-span">prosecutors, will wrap-span">ultimately decide whether Mr Trump is fit to occupy the White House. That is as it should be.

Further reading: Our background briefing on the Mueller report
